<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SACRAMENTO; 
</P>
<P>
MONTOYA'S JAIL TERM DELAYED BY APPEAL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Former state Sen. Joseph B. Montoya's scheduled date with prison was 
temporarily delayed when his attorneys filed a motion with the U.S. 9th Circuit 
Court of Appeals requesting bail while his case is under review. The Whittier 
Democrat, sentenced to 6 1/2 years in prison for his conviction on seven 
corruption charges, had been scheduled to report to prison Friday. But now it 
will be up to the appeals court to determine whether Montoya has a substantial 
chance of winning his appeal and therefore should be allowed to remain free on 
bail. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
APPEALS; MONTOYA, JOSEPH B; BAIL 
</P>
</SUBJECT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA062690-0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 238851 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
June 26, 1990, Tuesday, Home Edition 
</P>
