<HEADLINE>
<P>
7,000 PENGUINS DIE IN MYSTERY STAMPEDE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Reuters 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
SYDNEY, Australia 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
More than 7,000 King penguins, most of them chicks, were crushed to death on a 
remote Tasmanian island south of Australia in an apparent mass panic, wildlife 
officials said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
The officials said they are still unsure about the cause of the incident, which 
occurred about two weeks ago on Macquarie Island, a 67-square-mile nature 
reserve. The dead birds were piled up four deep when found a few days ago by 
wildlife officials, who likened the stampede to a crowd at a sports stadium. 
</P>
</TEXT>
