<HEADLINE>
<P>
SERIES OFFERS 2 SHOWS FOR AND ABOUT FAMILIES; 
</P>
<P>
THEATER: THE IN THE SPOTLIGHT CHILDREN'S DRAMA PROGRAM IS PRESENTING "CHEAPER 
BY THE DOZEN AND "YOU'RE A GOOD MAN, CHARLIE BROWN." 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CORINNE FLOCKEN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
YORBA LINDA 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Entertaining the family can run into big bucks, but the Yorba Linda Parks and 
Recreation Department is serving up an affordable alternative. 
</P>
<P>
Two family-oriented productions, complete with free ice cream at intermission, 
will be offered over the next three Saturday evenings as part of the city's 
1990 Summer Theater on the Green series. 
</P>
<P>
For a donation of $1 per person, families can stretch out under the stars at 
Hurless Barton Park and see a performance of the comedy "Cheaper by the Dozen" 
Saturday or the musical "You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown" July 7 or 14. 
</P>
<P>
In the Spotlight, a Yorba Linda-based actors' training program for children 3 
to 18, is producing the series, which opened with "Cheaper" Saturday to a 
capacity audience. 
</P>
<P>
"We think theater is something that families should experience together," said 
Robyn Naylor, executive producer of the series. The park setting "gives us all 
a chance to be out under the stars and start to appreciate the theatrical 
experience without a lot of expense and hassle." 
</P>
<P>
"Cheaper" is based on the book of reminiscences by Frank Gilbreth Jr. and 
Ernestine Gilbreth Carey about their father, a jocular efficiency expert who 
had his own theories about how to rear his 12-child family. 
</P>
<P>
Frank Gilbreth Sr., Naylor said, "figured you could take these dozen children, 
train them properly, send them out into the world, and they would all do just 
fine. It's a fun, accessible story about the real-life adventures of being a 
family." 
</P>
<P>
The play is set in the 1920s. The Spotlight production features an 18-member 
cast of youngsters ages 6 through 16 directed by Judy Sofer, a member of the 
Spotlight teaching staff. Naylor designed the period costumes, and Fullerton 
Civic Light Opera volunteers built the sets. 
</P>
<P>
Naylor's students also compose the cast of "Charlie Brown," the Broadway 
musical based on the child characters in the Charles Schulz comic strip. Paul 
Haggerty is the director for the musical. 
</P>
<P>
Naylor said she is coordinating the series at no charge to the city in order to 
give her young actors "the maximum opportunity to perform." 
</P>
<P>
"This outdoor experience will be totally different for them," she noted. "For 
example, there are no blackouts, so they had to learn how to exit by just 
walking quietly off the stage. It's a good lesson for them. 
</P>
<P>
"Plus, we're always telling our kids that the talent they have is a gift, and 
they need to have every chance they can to give the gift to other people." 
</P>
<P>
 "Cheaper by the Dozen" and "You're a Good Man, Charlie Brown" are 
presentations of the Yorba Linda Parks and Recreation Department Summer Theater 
on the Green series. "Cheaper" will be presented Saturday and "Charlie Brown" 
July 7 and 14 at Hurless Barton Park, Casa Loma Avenue between Yorba Linda 
Boulevard and Imperial Highway. Admission is free but officials ask donations 
of $1 per person. Show times are 7:30 p.m. Information: (714) 961-7160. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Cast rehearses fire drill scene from "Cheaper by the Dozen" at Barton 
Park. They are, front, Amanda Shannahan and Franco Avallone; and rear, Jesse 
Goodman, left, Mark Blair, Brent Garrison, Mandy Goodman, Oren Kaplan and Aaron 
Colacion. ROD BOREN / For The Times 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
<SUBJECT>
<P>
ARTS -- ORANGE COUNTY; YORBA LINDA (CA) -- CULTURE; PARKS -- ORANGE COUNTY; 
PLAYS; CHILDREN; FAMILIES; THEATER; MUSICALS 
</P>
