<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
DU PONT TO MARKET SOVIET DRUG 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By FROM TIMES WIRE SERVICES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
WASHINGTON 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Du Pont Co. announced today that it has received government approval to 
market the first Soviet drug licensed and clinically developed by an American 
pharmaceutical company. 
</P>
<P>
The company said the Food and Drug Administration agreed to permit the use of 
Ethmozine for the treatment of abnormal and life-threatening heart rhythms 
known as ventricular arrhythmias. 
</P>
<P>
These irregular heartbeats are caused by heart attack, coronary artery blockage 
and other disorders and are blamed for hundreds of thousands of deaths each 
year. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. John Mullane, director of drug development for Du Pont, said the drug was 
discovered in the late 1960s in Moscow and has been available in the Soviet 
Union for about 18 years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
